HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 867
By Moon
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Loretta Kuhn Cate.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Loretta Kuhn Cate; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Cate was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Loretta Cate was born in Knoxville on March 16, 1956, and raised in Rock
Island; her childhood was spent surrounded by family and playing outdoors, riding horses, and
enjoying time on the lake; and
WHEREAS, from an early age, Mrs. Cate was loving, compassionate, and fiercely
competitive; she graduated at the top of her class from Warren County High School in 1974;
and
WHEREAS, Loretta Cate attended Lipscomb College, playing as the number-two seed
for the women's tennis team during the 1974-1975 season after only learning how to play the
sport the previous summer; and
WHEREAS, she transferred to the University of Tennessee, Knoxville, and after
graduating, she attended the University of Tennessee College of Pharmacy, from which she
graduated with highest honors; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Cate's drive and incomparable work ethic paved the way for a highly
successful professional career; she began at Vanderbilt Hospital as a pediatric pharmacist
before transitioning into pharmaceutical sales with Parke-Davis; and
HJR0867
012693
- 1 -

WHEREAS, she excelled in every role she held, becoming the top district manager and
regional manager, the human resources manager, and, ultimately, the director of leadership
development, a post she held until her retirement in 2006; and
WHEREAS, in retirement, Loretta Cate founded her own company, Access Leadership
Edge, where she collaborated on client projects and long-term initiatives alongside a diverse
team of independent professionals; she also co-founded Women in Leadership Now and
continued to work on these passion projects until shortly before her passing; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Cate was a woman of deep faith and an active member of First United
Methodist Church in Maryville; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Cate showed Tennessee Walking Horses and won a world
championship at the Tennessee Walking Horse National Celebration in Shelbyville; she shared
this passion with her two daughters; and
WHEREAS, Loretta Cate was deeply devoted to her family, and she always endeavored
to remain true to family values of the highest order; her greatest joy was being with her children
and grandchildren; and
WHEREAS, she will be sadly mourned but fondly remembered by her husband of forty-
three years, Leslie Cate; daughters, Ashley Cate (Patrick Maximilian) Vogel and Lindsey Cate
(John Christopher) Salter; granddaughters, Elizabeth (Elle) Jacqueline Vogel, Vada June Vogel,
and Penelope Cate Salter; brothers, Charles William Kuhn, Jr., and Michael Roy Kuhn; and a
host of beloved nephews and cousins; and
WHEREAS, she was preceded in death by her parents, Charles William Kuhn and
Maxine Kuzzar Drake; and
WHEREAS, Loretta Cate leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all her chosen
endeavors; and
- 2 - 012693

WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Loretta Kuhn Cate, reflecting fondly upon her
impeccable character and her stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Cate.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
